</p>
<h2><b>End The Corporate Stranglehold On Health Care: Vote 
&quot;Yes&quot; On California Proposition 216</b></h2>
<h3>By Richard Alexander, Esq.</h3>
<p><hr><p><font size=-1>
San Jose, California attorney Richard Alexander, a National Honor Scholar at The Law School, University of Chicago, was certified as a civil trial advocate by the National Board of Trial Advocacy in 1980, has been specially recognized as a Trial Lawyer by the California Trial Lawyers Association, is a former member of the Board of Governors of The State Bar of California, currently serves as Vice President of Consumer Attorneys of California and is a founding member of the National Association of Consumer Advocates. He is the founder of <a href="http://www.alexanderlaw.com">The Alexander Law Firm</a> [http://www.alexanderlaw.com], a medium size law firm specializing in individual and class action litigation arising from negligence, toxic chemical, defective product, mass accident, environmental and fraud cases on behalf of consumers and small businesses. The firm holds Martindale-Hubbell's highest rating and is recognized in the List of Preeminent Law Firms in the United States. The firm sponsors <a href=http://consumerlawpage.com>The Consumer Law Page</a> [http://consumerlawpage.com] on the World Wide Web. Copyright Richard Alexander 1996.</font></p>
<hr>

</p>
<p>Wall Street investors and giant corporations have taken over our health care system by replacing 
traditional medical practices with &quot;managed care&quot; -- putting cost-cutting ahead of quality care and 
profits ahead of patients. </p>
<p>Managed care reaps billions for giant health corporations and rewards CEOs with staggering 
multi-million dollar paychecks. For example, the following is the value of stock owned by the 
CEOs of America's largest health businesses: </p>
<table>
<tr><td width=157>Leonard Abramson</td><td width=191>U.S. Healthcare </td><td width=115>$795.3 million</td></tr>
<tr><td width=157>Richard Scott</td><td width=191>Columbia/HCA </td><td width=115>$248.6 million</td></tr>
<tr><td width=157>David Jones</td><td width=191>Humana, Inc</td><td width=115>$232.6 million</td></tr>
<tr><td width=157>Richard Scrushy</td><td width=191>HealthSouth </td><td width=115>$186.7 million</td></tr>
<tr><td width=157>Malik Hasan</td><td width=191>HSI (Health Net) </td><td width=115>$141.3 million</td></tr>
<tr><td width=157>Daniel Crowley</td><td width=191>Foundation Health Corp. </td><td width=115>$40.7 million</td></tr>
<tr><td width=157>Alan Hoops</td><td width=191>PacifiCare Health Systems </td><td width=115>$35.0 million</td></tr>
<tr><td width=157>Jeffrey Barbakow</td><td width=191>Tenet</td><td width=115>$16.0 million</td></tr>
<tr><td width=157>Westcott W. Price III</td><td width=191>FHP (TakeCare) </td><td width=115>$12.8 million</td></tr>
</table>
<p>Yet, &quot;consumers are left to cope with health service cutbacks, substandard care, emergency room 
shutdowns, denial of needed treatment, and other cost management strategies designed to 
maximize profits&quot; That the conclusion reported in &quot;Wealth and Power: The U.S. Health Care 
Industry,&quot; Institute for Health &amp; Socio-Economic Policy, Feb. 1996. </p>
<p>More and more often, key medical decisions are being made by out-of-state accountants and 
bureaucrats instead of doctors and nurses. </p>
<p>How does this affect your care?</p>
<ul>
<li>Doctors and nurses are forced to sign &quot;loyalty oaths,&quot; putting their employers ahead of their 
patients. </li>
<li>&quot;Gag rules&quot; censor what doctors and nurses tell patients about treatment. </li>
<li>Access to specialists is restricted. </li>
<li>Bonuses are awarded to doctors for withholding treatment. </li>
<li>Patients are forced out of hospitals before they&#185;re fully recovered. </li>
<li>Registered nurses are replaced with less qualified, low-wage workers to care for patients. </li>
<li>Medical staffing is cut while doctors and nurses are assigned more patients. </li>
</ul>
<p>These practices are reaping lots of profits for giant health corporations. But the result for patients 
has been tragic, causing unnecessary injury and even death. </p>
<p>That's why over 800,000 California voters, led by the California Nurses Association and Prop 
103's Harvey Rosenfield, and endorsed by consumer advocate Ralph Nader, have joined 
together to pass the Patient Protection Act -- your health care bill of rights. Proposition 216 is 
your best chance to safeguard your right to quality health care, and to prevent unsafe and 
substandard medical care. </p>
<p>With the health care industry profit margins soaring by more than 300% since 1990, corporate 
opponents of Prop 216 will try to frighten voters about &quot;big government, more taxes.&quot; The 
insurers and HMOs know that their best chance to stop the Patient Protection Act is to create 
voter fear and confusion. They've already started spending millions of dollars to do exactly that -- 
and every cent they spend is subtracted from the health care you receive. </p>
<p>It's time for Californians to restore balance and accountability to an out-of-control health system 
that's risking patient lives and sacrificing quality care in greed-blinded pursuit of profits. It's time to 
put doctors, nurses, and patients back in control of our health system. It's time to put the caring 
back in health care. Vote YES on Proposition 216 this November for real patient protection.</p>
<h3><b>Proposition 216</b></h3>
<p><strong>The Patient Protection Act</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Outlaws bonuses to doctors for withholding treatment. </li>
<li>Bans &quot;Gag Rules&quot; restricting physicians and nurses from discussing treatment options with 
patients. </li>
<li>Establishes safe staffing levels for hospitals and nursing homes. Restricts the provision of 
patient care by inadequately trained personnel. </li>
<li>Ends denial of recommended medical treatment because it's &quot;too expensive&quot; or not offered 
by the HMO; requires written explanation and qualified second opinion for denial of claims. </li>
<li>Establishes a self-funded independent consumer watchdog group; requires industry 
disclosure of safety and financial data. </li>
<li>Bans the sale of your private medical records without your permission. </li>
<li>Requires detailed justification for increases in your premiums. </li>
<li>Pays for itself 100% by placing penalty fees on excessive HMO executive pay and 
multi-billion dollar mergers. This will fund all the costs for enforcing the Act, and will also 
help cover crucial community emergency and disease prevention programs. </li>
<li>Prevents industry-funded politicians from easily overriding these reforms in the Legislature 
once California voters have approved them. </li>
</ol>
<hr>
