</html>
</p>
<h2><a name="title">FEATURE: CONSUMER NEWS SPRING 1996</a></h2>
<hr>
<h3>FOOD LABELING CAMPAIGN.</h3>
<p>The National Consumer League, along with Public Voice for Food and Health Policy, has launched the &quot;Truth in Food Labeling 
Campaign.&quot; The program is designed to require identification of &quot;mechanically separated&quot; poultry. At present, products that are 
mechanically separated are labeled only as &quot;chicken&quot; or &quot;turkey,&quot; even though they may contain organs, bone, bone marrow, and 
skin. About 700 million pounds of mechanically separated poultry are used each year in foods such as hot dogs, bologna, salami, 
and some chicken nuggets. The campaign is also supported by Citizen Action and the Consumer Federation of America. For 
information, National Consumer League, 1701 K St., NW (#1200), Washington, DC 20006, 202-825-3323. </p>
<h3>LEMON ADS.</h3>
<p>The Center for Science in the Public Interest awarded its 11th annual Harlan Page Hubbard Lemon Awards for 1995 to 
companies with misleading, unfair, and irresponsible advertisements. The &quot;winners&quot; included promotion of excessive drinking, 
obscuring the true cost of an auto lease, and sample cigarettes received by people who don't smoke. For more information: 
Center for Science in the Public Interest, 1875 Connecticut Ave., NW, #300, Washington, DC 20009 (202-332-9110; e-mail: 
<a href="mailto:nah@essential.org">nah@essential.org</a>). </p>
<h3>CREDIT CARD RATES.</h3>
<p>Bankcard Holders of America reports the doubling of some credit card interest rates. Some consumers note seeing higher rates if 
they charge &quot;too much,&quot; while a bank may terminate a card if they think a consumer has not charged &quot; enough.&quot; Some consumers 
report their interest rate increased from 12.9 percent to 24.9 percent. For information: Bankcard Holders of America, 524 
Branch Dr., Salem , VA 24153; 703-389-5445. </p>
<h3>AUTO INSURANCE COSTS.</h3>
<p>The Pennsylvania Insurance Department has issued its annual Insurance Facts for Pennsylvania Consumer: Your Guide to Auto 
Insurance Premiums in Central Pennsylvania. This guide provides typical costs for various companies in selected counties. Also 
includes a question-and-answer format about various auto insurance concerns. For information: Insurance Dept., Room 1321 
Strawberry Square, Harrisburg, PA 17129, (717-787-2317). </p>
<h3>AUTO REPAIR CHANGES PROPOSED.</h3>
<p>Attorneys general from 43 states have called for reforms in the auto repair industry. The proposal calls for (1) elimination of 
contests, bonus programs, and sales quotas at repair shops; (2) disclosure when a &quot;flat-rate-manual&quot; instead of actual time is 
used to calculate the labor charge; and (3) increased disclosure to distinguish between recommended repairs and those that are 
necessary to correct the malfunction. </p>
<h3>COMMON CONSUMER COMPLAINTS.</h3>
<p>The Tennessee Division of Consumer Affairs reported the following as the most common sources of consumer complaints in 
1995; mail order, consumer credit, auto repair, home improvements, used car sales, contests, business opportunities, and lemon 
law. The efforts of this office resulted in more than one million dollars being returned to consumers last year. For information: 
Tennessee Division of Consumer Affairs, 500 James Robertson Parkway, 5th Floor, Nashville, TN 37240-0600 
(615-741-4737). </p>
<h3>INSURANCE GUIDE.</h3>
<p>The Office of Attorney General in Missouri has issued &quot;Insurance Coverage: Detecting Fraud, Long-Term Care Insurance, 
Medicare Supplemental Insurance Fraud.&quot; This brooklet offers suggestions when buying various insurance products and cautions 
consumers about potential deceptions. For information: Office of Attorney General, Box 899, Jefferson City, MO 65102 
(314-751-3321). </p>
<h3>FINANCIAL COUNSELING AND PLANNING.</h3>
<p>The 17 research-based articles in this annual journal include coverage of life cycle savings, retirement planning, homebuyers 
programs, personal economic stress, the financial well-being of older-women, financial asset ownership patters, and households 
with rent burdens. (Financial Counseling and Planning, Vol. 6, 1995, Association for Financial Counseling and Planning 
Education, 3900 East Camelback Rd., #200, Phoenix, AZ 85018; 602-912-5331; fax: 602-957-4828.) </p>
<h3>ALTERNATIVE FINANCIAL SECTOR.</h3>
<p>&quot;Lower-income consumers use a growing number of financial services including pawn shops, rent-to-own programs, 
check-cashing outlets, and rapid-refund tax services as alternatives to traditional financial services. These services constitute the 
Alternative Financial Sector (AFS). Compared to the traditional financial sector, AFS services are very expensive.&quot; The authors 
conclude that offers of &quot;quick cash&quot; and &quot;low payments&quot; make it difficult for counselors to steer clients to the &quot;slow and often 
difficult repair of financial management practices.&quot; (&quot;The Operations, Appeals and Costs of the Alternative Financial Sector: 
Implications for Financial Counselors,&quot; by Roger Swagler, John Burton, &amp; Joan Koonce Lewis, Financial Counseling and 
Planning, Vol. 6, 1995, pp. 93-98, Association for Financial Counseling and Planning Education, 3900 East Camelback Rd., 
#200, Phoenix, AZ 85018; 602-912-5331; fax: 602-957-4828.) </p>
<h3>FEE-ONLY FINANCIAL PLANNERS.</h3>
<p>A Money magazine investigation concluded that some financial planners who designate themselves as &quot;fee-only&quot; actually take 
commissions for selling securities or insurance. The study also revealed that 13 percent of the planning firms examined have had 
&quot;brushes with the law.&quot; While many fee-only planners provide solid advice and carefully avoid conflicts of interest, careful 
checking of an advisor's training, compensation method, and disciplinary record is vital. (&quot;The Big Bad News about Fee-Only 
Financial Planners,&quot; by Ruth Simon, Money, Dec., 1995, pp. 110-111, 113-114, 116, 118.) </p>
<h3>LOW-INCOME HOME BUYERS.</h3>
<p>Credit risks associated with a mortgage are accommodated through a variety of financial arrangements and institutions. The 
authors conclude that nondepository private-sector mortgage purchasers provide a method for investors to serve the mortgage 
needs of lower-income and of black and Hispanic borrowers, although accounting for a relatively small share of mortgages in 
1994. (&quot;Credit Risk and the Provision of Mortgages to Lower-Income and Minority Homebuyers,&quot; Federal Reserve Bulletin, 
Nov., 1995, pp. 989-1016.) </p>
<h3>PRIVACY.</h3>
<p>&quot;The typical consumer is on at least 25 marketing data bases. Some land on upwards of 100. There are more than 15,000 
specialized lists containing 2 billion consumer names--each representing a potential sale.&quot; This feature offers information on a 
variety of privacy-related concerns. (&quot;Marketers Tap Data We Once Called Our Own,&quot; by Bruce Horovitz, USA Today, Dec. 
19, 1995, pp. 1A-2A, 4B.) </p>
<h3>REVERSE MORTGAGES.</h3>
<p>The &quot;reverse&quot; mortgage allows older home owners to draw against the equity in their homes to receive a monthly income. This 
book offers a clear explanation and easy-to-follow calculations of the details and implications of a reverse mortgage. (Your New 
Retirement Nest Egg: A Consumer Guide to the New Reverse Mortgages, by Ken Scholen, 1995, 332 pp., paper, $24.95 plus 
$4.50 shipping, quantity discounts available, National Center for Home Equity Conversion, 7373 147th St., West Apple Valley, 
MN 55124; 612-953-4474.) </p>
<h3>AUTO GUIDE.</h3>
<p>Jack Gillis is back for the 16th year with his guide to the best and worst automobiles. This comprehensive resource guide covers 
buying strategies, safety features, fuel economy, maintenance, warranties, insurance, tires, and consumer protection assistance. 
More than 100 models are rated with easy-to-read, visually-oriented reviews covering safety, performance, comparative 
models, price, and operating costs. (Source: The Car Book 1996, by Jack Gillis, 224 pp., paper, $12.95, HarperCollins, 10 
East 53 Street, New York, NY 10022.) </p>
<h3>PERSONAL FINANCIAL PLANNING.</h3>
<p>This college textbook takes a life-situation and opportunity cost approach to budgeting, spending, career planning, taxes, 
insurance, investing, and retirement and estate planning. The &quot;Financial Planning in Action&quot; feature allows students to apply text 
concepts. The Personal Financial Planner (and Windows-version software) allows students to create and implement a personal 
financial plan. Instructional supplements include an instructor's manual (also on disk), study guide-readings book, a casebook, 
videos, a computerized testing program, and a Spanish glossary. (Personal Finance, 4th ed., by J. Kapoor. L. Dlabay, &amp; R. 
Hughes, 1996, 665 pages, Richard D. Irwin, Inc., 1333 Burr Ridge Parkway, Burr Ridge, IL 60521, 1-800-634-3961.) </p>
<h3>BUYING BONDS.</h3>
<p>The author takes the reader from bond basics to details about safety and investing in Treasury, municipal, corporate, and 
zero-coupon bonds. A major portion of the book covers mutual funds that specialize in bonds. A glossary provides details about 
key concepts related to bonds. (How to Buy Bonds The Smart Way, by Stephen Littauer, 1996, 243 pp., paper, $19.95, 
Dearborn Financial Publishing, 155 N. Wacker Dr., Chicago, IL 60606-1719; 1-800-829-7934.) </p>
<h3>MUTUAL FUND PORTFOLIO.</h3>
<p>&quot;Don't waste time searching for elusive risk-free investments&quot; is one of the 101 tips offered for a safe and profitable journey when 
building a mutual fund portfolio. Starting with mutual fund basics, the authors provide valuable assistance related to establishing 
goals, selecting funds, evaluating risk, and taxes. Most investors will find this a useful resource. (Building Your Mutual Fund 
Portfolio, by Albert J, Fredman &amp; Russ Wiles, 1996, 246 pp., cloth, $19.95, Dearborn Financial Publishing, 155 N. Wacker 
Dr., Chicago, IL 60606-1719; 1-800-829-7934.) </p>
<h3>CONSUMER MOVEMENT VIDEO.</h3>
<p>Over 20 pioneers and leaders were interviewed to provide viewers with excellent insight into the roots and accomplishments of 
the consumer movement. The video is organized to allow teachers to stop and discuss the material. A very useful teacher's guide 
includes key concepts, quotes, discussion questions, activities, and a glossary, along with a timeline of the consumer movement 
and an extensive resource list. (Change Makers: The Struggle for Consumer Rights, 1995, 56 min., VHS-format, $35 plus $5 
shipping, limited time introductory price, Consumer Research Foundation, 249 Perry St., Mill Valley, CA 94941; 
415-381-0825; fax: 415-381-3712.) </p>
<h3>TELEPHONE SCAMS.</h3>
<p>Telemarketing fraud and common telephone scams include prize offers, travel packages, vitamins, investments, charities, and 
recovery swindles. This brochure offers &quot;tip-offs to fraud&quot; as well as suggestions for protection from frauds and where to get 
additional help. (Telephone Scams and Older Consumers, free, Federal Trade Commission, Bureau of Consumer Protection, 
Washington, DC 20580.) </p>
<h3>CHANGE FOOD SAFETY LAWS?</h3>
<p>This publication is likely to expand the debate about methods for monitoring food safety. The introduction states that the 
&quot;Delaney clause was an inappropriate regulatory standard from the moment of its enactment.&quot; (Source: Modernize Our Food 
Safety Laws: Delete the Delaney Clause, 1995, 24 pp., $3.85, American Council on Science and Health, 1995 Broadway, 2nd 
Floor, New York, NY 10023-5860; 212-362-7044; fax: 212-362-4919.) </p>
<h3>CONSUMER CREDIT QUESTIONS.</h3>
<p>This booklet provides clear information on various concerns related to credit reports, credit bureaus, credit &quot;repair clinics,&quot; and 
opting out of mailing lists. (Source: 12 Common Questions about Consumer Credit and Direct Marketing, 1995, free, 20 pp., 
TRW Information, ATTN: Consumer Education, 701 TRW Parkway, Allen, TX 75013.) </p>
<h3>RETIREMENT SAVINGS.</h3>
<p>Proposed legislation to expand individual retirement accounts has been introduced in Congress. While proponents argue that 
these accounts can encourage a higher personal savings rate, recent economic research suggests that the effect of IRAs is 
minimal. (Source: &quot;The Impact of Individual Retirement Accounts on Savings,&quot; by Jonathan McCarthy &amp; Han N. Pham, Current 
Issues in Economics and Finance, Sept., 1995, free, Federal Reserve Bank of New York, Public Information Dept., 33 Liberty 
St., New York, NY 10045-0001; 212-720-6134.) </p>
<h3>DISASTER RIP-OFFS.</h3>
<p>A distinctive type of con-artist surfaces in the face of earthquakes, hurricanes, and other natural disasters. This newsletter 
provides detailed background information and warnings related to home repair contractors, charitable solicitations, advance fee 
loan scams, and con-artists posing as officials. (&quot;No Calm After the Storm: Rip-Off Artists Target Victims of Disaster,&quot; Senior 
Consumer Alert, Fall, 1995, 12 pp., free, American Association of Retired Persons, ATTN: Public Policy Institute, Rm. 
B6-340, 601 E St., NW, Washington, DC 20049.) </p>
<h3>LIFE INSURANCE INFORMATION.</h3>
<p>Life insurance industry representatives contend that &quot;consumers are much more informed today because state regulations require 
agents and companies to provide buyers with more and better information.&quot; In contrast, however, consumer professionals believe 
that &quot;it is cash value policies that Americans understand less about than virtually anything else they buy.&quot; (&quot;Are Consumers 
Adequately Informed About the Life Insurance Products They Purchase?,&quot; At Home With Consumers, Dec., 1995, 12 pp., free, 
Direct Selling Education Foundation, 1666 K St., NW, #1010, Washington, DC 20006; 202-293-5760; fax: 202-293-7483.) </p>
<h3>MENTAL POLLUTION.</h3>
<p>&quot;North Americans are drowning in a media-fed fantasy. We are the first culture in human history in which lives are shaped--not 
by nature--but by the beguiling images of mass media. We spend more hours watching nature shows than experiencing the real 
thing; more time laughing at TV jokes than joking around ourselves; more evenings experiencing TV sex than actually touching 
another human body. If we forego the role of participant in the real world, we become spectators in the flickering world of make 
believe.&quot; (Adbusters: The Journal of the Mental Environment, inside front cover, Issue 14, Winter, 1996, The Media Foundation, 
1243 West 7th Ave., Vancouver, BC V6H 1B7 Canada; 604-736-9401; fax: 604-737-6021.) </p>
<h3>SCANNER SCAMS.</h3>
<p>A six-month investigation by the Chicago Department of Consumer Services found that 55 percent of 208 stores checked 
allegedly overcharged customers due to errors in their scanner systems. Overcharges ranged from one cent to more than $23 for 
a single item. (NCAA News, Oct., 1995, p. 4, National Association of Consumer Agency Administrators, 1010 Vermont Ave., 
NW, Washington, DC 20005; 202-347-7395.) </p>
<h3>CREDIT UNION SATISFACTION.</h3>
<p>For the 12th straight year, credit unions ranked highest in consumer satisfaction among financial institutions. A survey conducted 
by the American Banker reports that 77 percent of credit union members are &quot;very satisfied&quot; with the quality of service they 
receive. That compares with 59 percent among bank and thrift customers. </p>
<h3>TIERED LENDING.</h3>
<p>&quot;Tiered loan pricing&quot; means that less-than-perfect borrowers may be able to get loans. However, they will pay more. Critics 
believe these punitive interest rates may be used to discriminate against women and minorities. (&quot;Tiered Lending Adjusts Rates to 
Each Customer,&quot; by Christine Dugas, USA Today, Nov. 16, 1995, pp. 1A, 2A.) </p>
<h3>TOP TELEVISION ADVERTISERS.</h3>
<p>McDonald's aired 2,829 commercials on network television during 1995. Other top television advertisers include AT&amp;T, MCI, 
Burger King, Sears, KFC, J.C. Penney, Wendy's, Red Lobster, and Tylenol. </p>
<hr>
