</h2>
<h2>Cutting Edge Litigation:</h2>
<h3>Computer Simulation and Animation in The Courtroom -- The New 
Wave</h3>
<h3>By Richard Alexander, Esq.</h3>
<hr><p><font size=-1>
San Jose, California attorney Richard Alexander, a National Honor Scholar at The Law School, University of Chicago, was certified as a civil trial advocate by the National Board of Trial Advocacy in 1980, has been specially recognized as a Trial Lawyer by the California Trial Lawyers Association, is a former member of the Board of Governors of The State Bar of California, currently serves as Vice President of Consumer Attorneys of California and is a founding member of the National Association of Consumer Advocates. He is the founder of <a href="http://www.alexanderlaw.com">The Alexander Law Firm</a> [http://www.alexanderlaw.com], a medium size law firm specializing in individual and class action litigation arising from negligence, toxic chemical, defective product, mass accident, environmental and fraud cases on behalf of consumers and small businesses. The firm holds Martindale-Hubbell's highest rating and is recognized in the List of Preeminent Law Firms in the United States. The firm sponsors <a href=http://consumerlawpage.com>The Consumer Law Page</a> [http://consumerlawpage.com] on the World Wide Web. Copyright Richard Alexander 1996.</font></p>
<hr>

<p>The advent of the computer has impacted and entered all arenas of every American profession. 
The court is no exception. Computers have already been used in court to provide visual 
simulations of car crashes,[1] three dimensional visual simulations of passenger aircraft crashes,[2] 
and to match the DNA structure of an accused with the perpetrator of a crime.[3] As computers 
capabilities increase with technology, courts are being forced to consider the extent to which 
computer illustrations and program based simulations will be allowed into the courtroom. 
Traditionally, courts have determined the admissibility of computer modeling through application of 
the &quot;<i>Frye</i> test,&quot;[4] which asks if proposed evidence has been &quot;sufficiently established to have 
gained general acceptance in the particular field in which it belongs.&quot;[5] This past summer the 
United States Supreme Court unanimously directed federal courts to abandon the <i>Frye</i> test in 
favor of a more liberal standard for admitting novel scientific evidence.[6] This more liberal 
standard, as set out in <i>Daubert,</i> will guide and advance the use of computer modeling in 
courtroom testimony. </p>
<p><strong>COMPUTER MODELING -- CAPABILITIES AND CATEGORIES </strong></p>
<p>All computer models can be stored on laser video discs. Among other things, these video discs 
require no rewinding or fast forwarding, can instantly bring up any desired frame of a presentation, 
can show an event from several possible vantage points, can condense display of deterioration of 
an object to a few minutes, and can highlight important focus points of a presentation. Computer 
models are powerful tools, capable of leaving a powerful, indelible impression on the trier of fact. </p>
<p>Different types of computer models serve different functions, and the admissibility of each type of 
model is dependent upon the model's function and the process through which the function is 
performed. For our purposes, computer modeling programs will be divided into four parts.[7] </p>
<p>In the first category the computer is used to arrive at solutions to standard, often used equations, 
such as those used for determining velocity, force of impact, or path of trajectory. The computer s 
usefulness in category 1 lies only in its ability to quickly and accurately determine solutions to 
otherwise complex and tedious equations. The data put into the computer and the computer s 
output can be easily verified. </p>
<p>The second category involves computer-generated graphics used to illustrate a proposed sequence 
of events as testified by an expert. The computer model in this category is similar to an artist's paint 
brush; the model is simply a tool which is controlled by the user. The quality and accuracy of the 
generated illustration is entirely dependent upon the knowledge and skill of the artist. The computer 
is not used to create events, it is only used to simplify an expert's testimony by the use of 
illustration. The expert's opinion is arrived at independently of the computer and the evidence is 
considered demonstrative rather than substantive. This computer model category has not been 
subject to the rigorous standards of the <i>Frye</i> test.[8] Category 2 illustrations will be admitted as 
evidence if they fairly and accurately reflect the oral testimony they supplement and do not unfairly 
bias the jury. </p>
<p>In contrast to category 2, the computer model in category 3 helps to formulate a theory to an 
event. Known variables are given to the computer, and from these variables, a computer is able to 
construct an illustration based upon standard equations programmed into the computer. For 
instance, in a case concerning an automobile collision, variables such as speed, mass of vehicle, 
and angle of impact, may be known. From the known variables, the computer estimates unknown 
variables and creates a simulation of the collision. The simulation program used by the computer as 
well as the computer's output can be examined and tested, but the output cannot feasibly be 
obtained without computer assistance. Because the computer model in category 3 is used as 
probative rather than demonstrative evidence, higher standards govern its admissibility as evidence. </p>
<p>Like category 3 computer models, category 4 models manipulate known variables to create an 
output and are used as probative evidence. Unlike category 3 models, however, the manner in 
which category 4 models manipulate data to achieve their output is too complex to be verified for 
accuracy. A simulation of a car crash using a category 4 model would be highly sophisticated, but, 
as a byproduct of this sophistication, the process used to derive the simulation would be too 
complex for examination. Thus, while category 4 models allow us to gain output that cannot 
otherwise be obtained, the model's usefulness is restricted by our inability to verify, by 
examination, an output. </p>
<p>While each category of computer modeling will be affected differently by the standards of 
<i>Daubert,</i> this step forward in recognizing new developments in science will liberalize admissibility 
of all categories. </p>
<p><strong>OVERVIEW AND EXTENT OF</strong><strong><i> DAUBERT </i></strong></p>
<p>The Supreme Court's tone in <i>Daubert</i> is guided by the liberal premise of Federal Rule of Evidence 
402 which states, &quot;[a]ll relevant evidence is admissible.&quot;[9] In <i>Daubert</i>, two minor children and 
their parents sued Merrell Dow Pharmaceuticals, Inc. claiming that the children's birth defects were 
caused by the mother's ingestion of Benedectin during pregnancy. Undisputed testimony 
established that in more than 30 published studies involving over 130,000 patients, maternal use of 
Bendectin during the first trimester of pregnancy was not shown to be a risk factor for human birth 
defects. In spite of these studies, plaintiffs used expert witness testimony to support their claim that 
Benedectin caused the childrens' birth defects. The experts based their testimony on one 
unpublished study which found a link between Benedectin and birth defects. The United State 
Court of Appeals dismissed the case, finding that because the study was unpublished, it was not 
subject to peer review and could not meet the Frye test of &quot;general acceptance.&quot; The Supreme 
Court, however, vacated the ruling of the Court of Appeals and unanimously held (Parts I and IIA 
of the Court's opinion) that Federal Rule of Evidence 7 02 superceded the <i>Frye</i> test, and that the 
<i>Frye</i> test was therefore inappropriate. Rule 702 states, &quot;If scientific, technical, or other specialized 
knowledge will assist the trier of fact to understand the evidence or to determine a fact in issue, a 
witness qualified as an expert by knowledge, skill, experience, training, or education, may testify 
thereto in the form of an opinion or otherwise.&quot; Nothing in Rule 702 requires &quot;general acceptance&quot; 
of the &quot;scientific, technical, or specialized knowledge&quot; sought to be admitted as evidence, so the 
Court reasoned, &quot;general acceptance&quot; is an inappropriate requirement to admission under Rule 
702. The Court stated, &quot;general acceptance is not a necessary precondition to the admission of 
scientific evidence.&quot; </p>
<p>While not binding on State courts, it is likely that <i>Daubert</i>, combined with modern criticism of the 
<i>Frye</i> test,[10] will soon extinguish use of <i>Frye</i> throughout the United States. The trier of fact, 
rather than the relevant expert community, will ultimately decide the place of novel scientific or 
technical knowledge in the court. </p>
<p>In Parts IIB, III and IV of <i>Daubert</i>, Justice Blackmun, joined by six other justices, attempts to 
provide guidelines for determining admissibility of scientific evidence under Rule 702. Although the 
Court's opinion specifically applies to scientific evidence,[11] state and lower federal courts will 
probably adopt Justice Blackmun's general language as the standard for determining admissibility 
of all technical and specialized evidence, including computer modeling.[12] Given an abandonment 
of the <i>Frye</i> test, Justice Blackmun's opinion in <i>Daubert</i> provides the only available standard for 
state and lower federal courts. </p>
<p><strong>GENERAL ADMISSIBILITY OF COMPUTER MODELING AS EVIDENCE </strong></p>
<p>The Court's majority describes trial judges as gatekeepers who have a duty to ensure that all 
evidence is reliable and relevant. The Court points out, however, that to be reliable, evidence does 
not have to be certain -- it is enough that &quot;good grounds&quot; for the evidence exists based upon what 
is known. Given this reasoning, computer models which construct a viable hypothesis based upon 
known facts can be reliable and should be admitted as evidence, even if the hypothesis cannot 
absolutely be proven as true. </p>
<p>The Court tests relevancy by asking if evidence has a &quot;valid scientific connection to the pertinent 
inquiry&quot; -- if a model addresses a significant issue in a case. In a further effort to guide lower courts 
in their determination of &quot;reliability and relevancy,&quot; the Supreme Court lists several factors 
important in determining whether novel scientific evidence can be admitted into the court. </p>
<p>First, the Court asked if evidence can be, or has been, tested to ensure that proposed evidence 
will yield true results and have a strong resistance to falsification. Second, the Court considered if 
evidence has been subject to &quot;peer review and publication.&quot; The Court reasons that flaws in a 
novel theory are best discovered and exposed by review from peers in the field. Third, the Court 
considered the &quot;standards controlling the technique's operation&quot; and the level of a known or 
potential rate of error resulting from the technique's operation. If a theory cannot, or is not, applied 
efficiently, or yields a high rate of error in application, it cannot be considered reliable. Fourth, the 
court maintained that while not dispositive, &quot;general acceptance&quot; has some bearing on evidence 
reliability. </p>
<p>Thus, even though the <i>Frye</i> test is no longer the single standard determining the admissibility of 
novel scientific or technical evidence, &quot;general acceptance&quot; is still one consideration in determining 
admissibility of evidence under Rule 702. </p>
<p>Finally, pursuant to Federal Rule of Evidence 403, the Court considers whether the &quot;probative 
value [of the evidence] is substantially outweighed by the danger of unfair prejudice, confusion of 
the issues, or misleading the jury . . . .&quot;[13] So even though a computer model is determined to be 
relevant and reliable, a court can bar the model from introduction as evidence if the model will 
prejudice the jury. For example, a category 2 illustration of a vehicle accident involving a 
decapitation may yield the most accurate illustration of the accid ent possible, but if too graphic, 
the illustration may be barred as evidence. </p>
<p>None of the tests suggested by the Supreme Court, however, are individually required. The tests 
are to be considered in the aggregate along with other relevant factors. The Court takes the 
position that the trier of fact, not a specialized community, should determine evidence validity. The 
Court reasoned, &quot;[v]igorous cross-examination, presentation of contrary evidence, and careful 
instruction on the burden of proof are the traditional and appropriate means of attacking shaky but 
admissible evidence.&quot; Under the Court's liberal view &quot;pertinent evidence based upon scientifically 
valid principles&quot; meets the admissibility standards of Rule 702 and should be admitted, even if the 
evidence has not been generally accepted. </p>
<p><strong>ADMISSIBILITY OF VARIOUS COMPUTER MODELS AS EVIDENCE </strong></p>
<p>Under the new &quot;<i>Dauber</i>t test&quot; it is likely that computer modeling categories 1-3 will be allowed 
into evidence, while the future of category 4 computer models remains uncertain. </p>
<p>Category 1 involves formulas which meet all of the admissibility tests under <i>Daubert</i>. These 
formulas have been reviewed and accepted by experts in the field, and computers are able to 
apply these formulas with a lower rate of error than can be done without the use of a computer. 
Courts should freely allow the use of category 1 computer models as an aid to evidence gathering. </p>
<p>Category 2 models, computer illustrations, will also be liberally admitted into evidence. An 
illustration must fairly and accurately reflect the oral testimony it supplements without unfairly 
biasing the jury, but whether an illustration was created by computer or hand is irrelevant to is 
admissibility. </p>
<p>The output from category 3 computer models cannot generally be obtained without a computer, 
but the model's data, formula, and output can be verified. Based on the Supreme Court's language 
in <i>Daubert</i>, the fact that a computer was needed to obtain a given output does not preclude that 
output from being admitted as evidence. The Court stated, &quot;[t]he focus of course must be solely on 
principles and methodology, not on the conclusions that they generate.&quot; DNA matching techniques 
provide one example of controversial category 3 evidence which is gaining acceptance in the 
courts. In allowing computer aided DNA matching, the Hawaii Supreme Court found a model to 
be admissible as evidence when the model's underlying data and the procedure used to obtain the 
model were found valid.[14] As long as the program and data used in a category 3 computer 
model are reviewable and meet the criteria of <i>Daubert</i>, the output generated should be admissible 
as evidence. Furthermore, as substantive evidence, category 3 computer models can be replayed 
by the jury during deliberation.[15] </p>
<p>Category 4, often referred to as the &quot;black box,&quot; involves computer programs that cannot be 
thoroughly analyzed or tested. Thus, while the underlying principle of the proposed evidence can 
be subject to peer review and verified, the validity of the technique applying this principle cannot 
be examined. Because it is difficult to test the model for &quot;falsability&quot; or accuracy, because the 
model's operational techniques cannot be examined, and because the model may have trouble 
gaining general acceptance, category 4 computer models will often be precluded from admission 
into evidence under the Daubert test. Courts are reluctant to admit computer evidence when the 
program, output, or underlying data cannot be examined by the opposing party.[16] However, if a 
complex computer model's accuracy, security, low error rate, and general acceptance can be 
verified through empirical use and testing of the model, the model should be admitted into evidence 
under the new <i>Daubert</i> test. Moreover, the Court's statement that &quot;traditional barriers to opinion 
testimony&quot; should be relaxed so that &quot;traditional but appropriate means of attacking shaky but 
admissible evidence&quot; can be implemented, sends a strong message that even marginally supported 
evidence should be presented for consideration by the trier of fact. </p>
<p><strong>CONCLUSION</strong> </p>
<p>By abolishing the outdated <i>Frye</i> test and liberalizing admittance of evidence under Rule 702, the 
Supreme Court has allowed courts to keep pace with advancing technology and to achieve a more 
efficient and just legal system. Today, even specialized communities are inundated with advancing 
technologies, and new technology is able to achieve reliability and validity long before it can 
achieve &quot;general acceptance.&quot; In allowing the trier of fact to be exposed to controversial evidence, 
the Court has not taken reviewability of a novel theory out of the hands of those most capable of 
judging the theory; the validity of scientific or technical evidence will still be based on and 
determined by testimony from the appropriate expert community. The Court has simply allowed 
the trier of facts an opportunity to hear evidence offered, and to reconcile conflicting opinions 
among the expert community. Liberally allowing evidence to be presented before the jury is 
consistent with the idea that only a judge or jury may make factual conclusions in a given case. 
Whether a theory or model provides an accurate account of reality is a factual determination. The 
Court's decision in <i>Daubert</i> will preserve powers constitutionally vested to the trier of fact and 
enable the courts to keep pace with rising technology of computer models. </p>
<p>[1] <i>Shaeffer v. General Motors Corp.</i>, 372 Mass 171 360 NE2d 1062 (1977). </p>
<p>[2] Fadely, Kathlynn G., &quot;Use of Technology in Aviation Litigation,&quot; U.S. Department of Justice 
(1992). </p>
<p>[3] <i>Hawaii v. Montalbo</i>, 73 Haw 130 (1992). </p>
<p>[4] Leading cases are <i>Schaeffer v. GM</i>, 360 N.E.2d 1062 (Mass. 1977) and <i>Starr v. Campos</i> 
655 P.2d 794 (Ariz. App. 1982). </p>
<p>[5] <i>Frye v. United States</i>, 54 App. D.C. 46, 47, 293 F. 1013, 1014 (1923). </p>
<p>[6] <i>Daubert v. Merrell Dow Pharmaceuticals, Inc.</i>, 93 C.D.O.S. 4825, 4826 (June 28,1993). </p>
<p>[7] Bohan, Thomas L., &quot;Computer-Aided Accident Reconstruction: Its Role in Court,&quot; (1991). </p>
<p>[8] <i>People v. McHugh</i>, 476 N.Y.S. 2d 721 (Sup. Ct. 1984). </p>
<p>[9] Calif. Rule of Evid. 351 adopts this same language. </p>
<p>[10] See P. Giannelli, &quot;The Admissibility of Novel Scientific Evidence: Frye v. United States, a 
Half-Century Later,&quot; 80 Colum. L. Rev. 1197, 1200-01 (1980). </p>
<p>[11] See footnote 8 of the majority opinion. </p>
<p>[12] In his dissent, Chief Justice Rehnquist sharply criticized the majority's failure to provide lower 
courts with clearer guidelines. Chief Justice Rehnquist writes, &quot;Questions arise simply from reading 
this part of the Court's opinion, and countless more questions will surely arise when hundreds of 
district judges try to apply its teaching to particular offers of expert testimony. Does all of this dicta 
apply to an expert seeking to testify on the basis of 'technical or other specialized knowledge' -- 
the other types of expert knowledge to which Rule 702 applies -- or are the 'general observations' 
limited only to 'scientific knowledge'? What is the difference between scientific knowledge and 
technical knowledge; does Rule 702 actually contemplate that the phrase 'scientific, technical, or 
other specialized knowledge' be broken down into numerous subspecies of expertise, or did its 
authors simply pick general descriptive language covering the sort of expert testimony which courts 
have customarily received?&quot; </p>
<p>[13] Equivalent language is found in Calif. Rule of Evid. 352. </p>
<p>[14] Computer modeling accounts for only one of many controversial procedures used in DNA 
matching. See<i> Hawaii v. Montalbo</i>, 73 Haw. 130 (1992) (allowing DNA matching procedure). </p>
<p>[15] Weinberg, David, &quot;Seeing is Believing: The Use of Scientific Animation in Motor Vehicle 
Cases,&quot; Engineering Animation Inc. (1993). </p>
<p>[16] <i>Mississippi PSC v. Mississippi Valley Gas Co.</i>, 358 So.2d 418 (Miss. 1978). </p>
