<h2>A Special Message to Lawyers Visiting This Site: A Rising Tide Raises All Ships - Join Me on 
the Web</h2>
<h4>By Richard Alexander, Esq.</h4>
<hr><p><font size=-1>
San Jose, California attorney Richard Alexander, a National Honor Scholar at The Law School, University of Chicago, was certified as a civil trial advocate by the National Board of Trial Advocacy in 1980, has been specially recognized as a Trial Lawyer by the California Trial Lawyers Association, is a former member of the Board of Governors of The State Bar of California, currently serves as Vice President of Consumer Attorneys of California and is a founding member of the National Association of Consumer Advocates. He is the founder of <a href="http://www.alexanderlaw.com">The Alexander Law Firm</a> [http://www.alexanderlaw.com], a medium size law firm specializing in individual and class action litigation arising from negligence, toxic chemical, defective product, mass accident, environmental and fraud cases on behalf of consumers and small businesses. The firm holds Martindale-Hubbell's highest rating and is recognized in the List of Preeminent Law Firms in the United States. The firm sponsors <a href=http://consumerlawpage.com>The Consumer Law Page</a> [http://consumerlawpage.com] on the World Wide Web. Copyright Richard Alexander 1996.</font></p>
<hr>


<p>Today in the United States we could not pass the Bill of Rights. </p>
<p>Although Americans live in the most complicated legal system in the history of the world, law related education is not taught in schools. </p>
<p>The average citizen knows little about our legal system and has no idea of the thousands of laws and regulations that impact every aspect of their daily lives. </p>
<p>It would be bad enough if the public were simply ignorant, but it is worse than that.</p>
<p>The average person is bombarded by the media with news of lawsuits from across the country. These daily news stories report weird, peculiar and unusual 
occurrences, which present a very distorted view of our legal system. Unfortunately this &quot;news&quot; is not just reported. It is repeated in morning papers, drive-time 
radio, discussed at work, and reported again on television. Repetition is the foundation of education, but in this case it is mis-education and as a result many 
Americans today believe the law and our system of justice makes no sense and they are outraged. </p>
<p>Add corporate America's readiness to blame the lawyers for laws passed by Congress and state legislatures and every conceivable management error. Include 
diatribes by public officials, such as a former Vice President Dan Quayle who blamed lawyers for decreased manufacturing productivity. Consider the local car 
dealer's advertisements that routinely blame lawyers when consumer information is provided as required by law. </p>
<p>Lawyers and the legal system are under daily attack and nobody is fighting back.</p>
<p>The end result is that the public believes that our courts and system of justice is not working because lawyers are at fault. For an electorate to be this mis-informed is 
not healthy in a democracy.</p>
<p>For years I thought that public legal education could only be accomplished by statewide advertising sponsored by the organized bar. Today I have changed my 
mind. The World Wide Web is providing lawyers and the profession with the means to do what we does best -- educate. And it can be done at a fraction of the 
cost of traditional mass media.</p>
<p>The central strength of the net is that it allows lawyers as information professionals to provide knowledge that the public can use on demand. The web is not the 
place to publish a firm brochure that nobody will look at more than once, but rather a medium for you to share your expertise in specific areas of the law and to give 
the public the information that it cannot get from any other place.</p>
<p>For example, for twenty years I wrote law reviews and journal articles and newspaper editorials that were published and promptly buried in libraries where only the 
most stalwart could find them.. Today I publish those same articles on my web site that is fully indexed by fifty search engines, open 24 hours a day and instantly 
available to anyone who can open All-in-One [<a href="http://www.albany.net/allinone/all1www.html#WWW">http://www.albany.net/allinone/all1www.html#WWW</a>].</p>
<p>The World Wide Web allows you to serve the public's need for information and to provide the detailed information that sophisticated purchasers of legal services 
want. In doing so it helps the public better understand how to select the right professional for a given problem. </p>
<p>From my years on the Board of Governors of The State Bar of California I know the great difficulty that the public has in finding the right lawyer. I attended many 
public hearings concerning the need to improve our system of discipline and although I heard many people complain about their lawyer, I never heard one person 
ever admit that they had selected the wrong lawyer in the first place, which was often the case. </p>
<p>The public does not choose lawyers with the dedication they bring to buying a car and most have no idea what the average corporate general counsel does to find 
the right lawyer in a given locality for a special case or assignment. </p>
<p>When consumers can find the &quot;right&quot; lawyer who is experienced and knowledgeable, many complaints about lawyers will come to an end. But finding the &quot;right&quot; 
lawyer is difficult, even for attorneys, and it takes a substantial amount of time, effort and sophistication. For non-lawyers it is a daunting task. The web makes the 
process easy for the average person. </p>
<p>For example my website is filled with substantive information about my practice and it is easy to use. Anyone interested in fighting fraud, defective products, toxic 
chemicals, pollution, insurance, banking, credit, loans, disability, medicine, cancer, dioxins, asthma, safety, injury prevention, head injuries, home hazards, radon, 
families, adoption, abuse prevention, legal negotiations, finding the &quot;right&quot; lawyer, or understanding a fee agreement consumer complaints, and class actions can find 
forty articles, more than 100 brochures and approximately 900 links to sites we use in our practice on topics ranging from the location of archives, libraries and 
university databases, defective products, disability, disaster relief: fire and earthquake, environment, legal sources, medical resources, parenting and family, safety 
and injury prevention, statutes, codes, rules, and regulations, toxic chemicals, U.S. government, to violence and abuse prevention. If you are new to the web open 
my site and spend an enjoyable evening learning what is on the net that can benefit you, your clients and your practice [<a href="http://www.seamless.com/alexanderlaw/">http://www.seamless.com/alexanderlaw/</a>].</p>
<p>At the same time that visitors are finding helpful information if they are interested they can learn about my practice by opening my firm brochure, check my 
references, records of cases won and lost, articles published, speaking engagements, a list of distinctions and awards, our current class action cases for consumers 
and small businesses, plus a statement of my philosophy and the background and experience of the great lawyers in my firm. </p>
<p>If a visitor has a specific problem they would like us to consider, they can open <a href="http://seamless.com/alexanderlaw/ques.html">How To Become A Client</a> and provide me with a thumbnail sketch of the case. For 
those we cannot help we provide a list of lawyers in their home state and recommend they read my article on &quot;<a href="howhire.shtml">How to Hire the 'Right' Lawyer</a>.&quot;</p>
<p>Because we are committed to sharing information with the public and the profession my site has won a number of awards, including Three Stars from 
<a href="http://www.mckinley.com/">Magellan/McKinley</a> and it also was selected as being in the Top Five Percent on the Web by <a href="http://www.pointcom.com">Point</a>. My site is linked on more than 800 sites, which I am told is 
more than West Law and my firm is obviously no match for West Publishing Company in marketing or economic power. [It was recently sold to a Canadian 
company for $2+ Billion] </p>
<p>This is the reason our site has had more than 1,000,000 visitors in the first six months of 1996 -- more traffic than <a href="http://www.counsel.com">Lexis Counsel Connect</a> and currently we have 
more than 50,000 visitors a week opening our various sources of information, which we regularly update. </p>
<p>The Internet is a gigantic step forward in public information and with its exponential growth I am hopeful that an increasingly sophisticated public will use the Internet 
to make better decisions about selecting lawyers.</p>
<p>One thing is sure. Our profession coined the words &quot;pro bono publico.&quot; Public service is something lawyers do all the time, across the U.S., with myriad programs 
that are excellent but which receive little publicity. The net changes all that forever.</p>
<p>With the explosive potential of the internet in its infancy we are at the threshold of a new beginning in sharing information that will eclipse the printing press. I am 
thrilled to be a part of it and I want you to join me.</p>
<p>A rising tide raises all ships. Share yourself with the public and you raise not only your practice, but everyone's. Provide free information and helpful advice. It is a 
win-win situation. Thousands of people will find out who you are and what you do and what is more, by providing needed information you can help people solve 
problems.</p>
<p>You went to law school to make a difference and the web is going to allow you to achieve that dream. The thank you letters and fan mail that will come your way 
will make it more than worthwhile. </p>
<hr>
